Butterfly Chart

Cancer Incidence Rates and Mortality between HDI/Sex

Photo by Angiola Harry on Unsplash

Cancer cannot cripple love, it cannot shatter hope, it cannot conquer the spirit…
—Unknown

Butterfly plot is a graphical representation for comparing two treatment responses for the same subject across different categories. They are also called tornado plots or pyramid plots.

Load Data

the life expectancy and income of 182 nations

df <- read.csv("archetypes/global-cancer-data/cancer-incidence-mortality.csv", header = TRUE, stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
df

Wrangle the data

Note that since buttefly plots are plotted for comparison against a y-axis. We need to convert one of our columns to negative.

the_order <- rev(df$Cancer[1:10]) #to set limits in plotting

df$Number_Incidence <- df$Number_Incidence*(-1) #convert to negative

df1 <- df %>%
  slice_head(n=10)%>%
  rename(Incidence = Number_Incidence, Mortality = Number_Deaths)%>%
  gather(key, value, -c(Cancer))

First example of a Butterfly Plot

theme_opts <- theme(
    text = element_text(family = "inconsolata"), 
    plot.title = element_text(color = "black", size = 30, face = "bold"),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(color = "black", size = 20),
    plot.caption = element_text(color = "#555555", size = 20, face = "bold"),
    axis.text = element_text(color = "#555555", size = 20, face = "bold"),
    axis.title=element_text(size=20,face="bold"),
    panel.border = element_blank(),
    panel.background = element_blank(),
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank(), # remove minor gridlines
    legend.title = element_blank(), # remove legend title
    legend.text = element_text(color = "black", size = 20),
    legend.position = "top",
    legend.margin  = unit(0.1, "lines"),
    legend.text.align = 0)
  
# plot
v1 <- 
  df1 %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Cancer, y = value, group = key, fill = key)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", width = 0.75) +
  coord_flip() +
  scale_x_discrete(limits = the_order) +
  labs(title = "Cancer Incidence and Mortality Rates") +
  theme_bw() +
  theme_opts
  # reverse the order of items in legend
  # guides(fill = guide_legend(reverse = TRUE)) +
  # scale_fill_manual(values=c("red", "blue"), # change the default colors of bars
  #                   name="",
  #                   breaks=c("Incidence", "Mortality"),
  #                   labels=c("Incidence", "Mortality")) 


girafe(ggobj = v1, width_svg = 1280/72, height_svg = 720/72,
       options = list(opts_sizing(rescale = TRUE, width = 1.0)))

Second Example with Labels overlayed

theme_opts2 <- theme(text = element_text(color = "#3A3F4A"),
    panel.grid.major.y = element_blank(),
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
    panel.grid.major.x = element_line(linetype = "dotted", size = 0.3, color = "#3A3F4A"),
    axis.title = element_blank(),
    plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", size = 36, margin = margin(b = 10), hjust = 0.030),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 16, margin = margin(b = 20), hjust = 0.030),
    plot.caption = element_text(size = 14, margin = margin(b = 10, t = 50), color = "#5D646F"),
    axis.text.x = element_text(size = 12, color = "#5D646F"),
    axis.text.y = element_blank(),
    strip.text = element_text(color = "#5D646F", size = 18, face = "bold", hjust = 0.030),
    plot.background = element_rect(fill = "#EFF2F4"),
    plot.margin = unit(c(2, 2, 2, 2), "cm"),
    legend.position = "top",
    legend.margin  = unit(0.1, "lines"),
    legend.text  = element_text(family = "Ubuntu Condensed", size = 20),
    legend.text.align = 0)


v2 <- ggplot(df1, aes(x = Cancer, color = key))+
  geom_linerange(data = df1[df1$key=="Incidence",], 
                 aes(ymin = -0.3, ymax = -0.3+value), size = 15, alpha = 0.8)+
  geom_linerange(data = df1[df1$key=="Mortality",], 
                 aes(ymin = 0.3, ymax = 0.3+value), size = 15, alpha = 0.8)+
  geom_label(aes(x = Cancer, y = 0, label = Cancer, family = "Ubuntu Condensed"), 
         inherit.aes = F,
         size = 8, label.padding = unit(0.0, "lines"), label.size = 0,
         label.r = unit(0.0, "lines"), fill = "#EFF2F4", alpha = 0.5, color = "#5D646F")+
  coord_flip()+
  scale_x_discrete(limits = the_order) +
  labs(x = "Type of Cancer", y = "Value", title = "Cancer Incidence and Mortality Rates")+
  scale_color_manual(name = "", values = c(Incidence = "#77dff7", Mortality = "#ff5973"),
                 labels = c("Incidence", "Mortality"))+
  theme_minimal(base_family = "Ubuntu Condensed")+
  theme_opts2

  



girafe(ggobj = v2, width_svg = 1280/72, height_svg = 720/72,
       options = list(opts_sizing(rescale = TRUE, width = 1.0)))

Save plot

as vector or raster image

# full version
ggsave(filename = "assets/globalcan-fs.svg", plot = v1, width=1280/72, height=720/72)


ggsave(filename = "assets/globalcan-sm.svg", plot = v2, width=4, height=2.25)
